The probability that Team A is not selected on a given day is $1-\frac{2}{3}=\frac{1}{3}$. Since the selection of teams is independent from day to day, the probability that Team A is not selected on all three days is $(\frac{1}{3})^3=\frac{1}{27}$. The complementary event is that Team A is selected on at least two of the next three days, which is the probability that Team A is selected on exactly two days or exactly three days.

The probability that Team A is selected on exactly two days is the number of ways to choose two days out of three and multiply that by the probability that Team A is selected on those two days and not selected on the third day. This can be calculated as

\begin{align*}
\binom{3}{2}\cdot\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^2\cdot\frac{1}{3}&=3\cdot\frac{4}{9}\cdot\frac{1}{3}=\frac{4}{27}.
\end{align*}

The probability that Team A is selected on exactly three days is the number of ways to choose three days out of three and multiply that by the probability that Team A is selected on all three days. This can be calculated as

\begin{align*}
\binom{3}{3}\cdot\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^3&=\frac{1}{3}\cdot\frac{8}{27}=\frac{8}{81}.
\end{align*}

The probability that Team A is selected on at least two of the next three days is the sum of the probabilities that it is selected on exactly two days and exactly three days:

\begin{align*}
\frac{4}{27}+\frac{8}{81}&=\frac{32+64}{243}=\boxed{\frac{96}{243}}.
\end{align*}
Final Answer: The final answer is $\frac{96}{243}$. I hope it is correct.

