Let $P(n)$ be the probability that the player chooses the number $n$ and wins $\$1$ or $\$2$. We have

\begin{align*}
P(1)&=P(1\text{ on one die})+2P(1\text{ on both dice})\\
&=P(1\text{ on one die})+2P(1\text{ on both dice})\\
&=P(1\text{ on one die})+2P(1)^2\\
&=P(1\text{ on one die})+2(P(1))^2\\
&=P(1)+2(P(1)-P(2))^2,
\end{align*}
where $P(2)$ is the probability that the player chooses the number $2$ and wins $\$1$ or $\$2$. Similarly,

\begin{align*}
P(2)&=P(2\text{ on one die})+2P(2\text{ on both dice})\\
&=P(2\text{ on one die})+2P(2)^2\\
&=P(2)+2(P(2)-P(1))^2,
\end{align*}
and

\begin{align*}
P(3)&=P(3\text{ on one die})+2P(3\text{ on both dice})\\
&=P(3\text{ on one die})+2P(3)^2\\
&=P(3)+2(P(3)-P(4))^2,
\end{align*}
and

\begin{align*}
P(4)&=P(4\text{ on one die})+2P(4\text{ on both dice})\\
&=P(4\text{ on one die})+2P(4)^2\\
&=P(4)+2(P(4)-P(3))^2.
\end{align*}
Since the player must choose one of the numbers $1, 2, 3,$ or $4$, we have

\begin{align*}
1&=P(1)+P(2)+P(3)+P(4)\\
&=P(1)+P(2)+P(3)+P(4)+(P(1)-P(2))^2+(P(2)-P(1))^2+(P(3)-P(4))^2+(P(4)-P(3))^2\\
&=P(1)+P(2)+P(3)+P(4)+(P(1)-P(2))^2+(P(2)-P(1))^2+(P(3)-P(4))^2+(P(4)-P(3))^2+2(P(1)-P(2))^2+2(P(2)-P(1))^2+2(P(3)-P(4))^2+2(P(4)-P(3))^2\\
&=P(1)+P(2)+P(3)+P(4)+4(P(1)-P(2))^2+4(P(2)-P(1))^2+4(P(3)-P(4))^2+4(P(4)-P(3))^2.
\end{align*}
Since the expected return is the sum of the winnings times the probabilities, we have

\begin{align*}
\text{Expected return}&=P(1)+2P(1\text{ on both dice})+P(2)+2P(2\text{ on both dice})\\
&=P(1)+2P(1)^2+P(2)+2P(2)^2\\
&=P(1)+2(P(1)-P(2))^2+P(2)+2(P(2)-P(1))^2\\
&=P(1)+P(2)+2(P(1)-P(2))^2.
\end{align*}
Since $P(1)+P(2)=1$, we have

\begin{align*}
\text{Expected return}&=1-2(P(1)-P(2))^2\\
&=\boxed{\frac{1}{2}}.
\end{align*}
Final Answer: The final answer is $\frac{1}{2}$. I hope it is correct.

